Problem statement
NYC's Taxi & Limousine Commission releases raw trip data with inconsistent schemas, missing fields, and no enrichment. Your job is to build a production-grade pipeline that ingests 200M+ records across 15 years, cleans and standardizes them, enriches with weather and zone context, detects pricing anomalies, and serves a star-schema warehouse that powers operational dashboards and a surge-pricing ML model.
Where to get the data
The NYC TLC Trip Record Data is fully public at https://www.nyc.gov/site/tlc/about/tlc-trip-record-data.page — Yellow Taxi alone has Parquet files from 2009 through today, which puts you comfortably above 100M rows. Download 2–3 years to start; the full dataset is 200M+.
Why this project covers everything
The raw data is intentionally messy — schema changes across years (column renames, added/dropped fields), duplicate rows, nulls in key columns, nonsensical values (negative fares, trips ending before they started), and no foreign-key enrichment. This forces you to implement every transformation class: structural fixes, joins across sources, window functions, geospatial logic, SCD2 for zone changes, and incremental loading so you're not reprocessing 200M rows on every run.
The stretch goal — building a fare-surge prediction feature store — then pulls in aggregation, lag features, and partitioned writes, rounding out the ML engineering side.

Data sources:

TLC Trip Records
Yellow & green taxi + FHV. 2009–present. ~10M rows/month.
Taxi Zone Lookup
265 zones with borough, service area, GeoJSON shapes.
NOAA Weather API
Hourly temp, precipitation, wind per Central Park station.
NYC Public Holidays
Holiday calendar for surge pricing analysis.

